A RISTOTLE.

The Hirundo feeds on flesh, and lays eggs twice a year, for the whole winter also it lies hid. The way of brutes upon the whole bears a marked like- ness to the life of man, and more so in the smaller than the larger kinds. One may observe the under- standing way which the Hirundo foremost in the ranks of birds shews in the constitution and con- struction of its nest. It builds it by applying mud to straWS‚ after the rule of daub and wattle work, and if there ever be a scarcity of mud, it wets itself and rolls itself in dust with all its feathers.
